  "prompt": "What's the origin of the expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\"?",
  "response": "The expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" is most famously associated with the character John McClane, played by Bruce Willis, in the \"Die Hard\" film series. It first appeared in the original \"Die Hard\" movie released in 1988. The phrase became iconic when McClane uses it as a taunt, followed by an expletive, to antagonize the villain. \n\nThe words themselves are reminiscent of old Westerns or cowboy lingo, which often included exuberant cries like \"Yippee\" or \"Yeehaw\" as expressions of joy or excitement. \"Ki-Yay\" doesn't have a specific meaning but complements \"Yippee\" with a rhythmic, playful sound. The phrase's informal, slightly rebellious tone contributes to its lasting appeal and its association with the brash, fearless character of McClane.",
